gotten a lifelong rundown of
what was in store.

50:54.151 --> 50:57.922 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That's how I knew to wear
flip-flops in the
shower or to take notes in class
or that visits

50:57.955 --> 51:00.858 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to the writing center were
covered by tuition.

51:00.891 --> 51:03.027 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But there was still a lot I
couldn't figure
out this way.

51:03.060 --> 51:07.031 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For instance, I dropped a class
after realizing
the textbooks would cost a
couple hundred

51:07.064 --> 51:08.799 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
dollars.

51:08.832 --> 51:11.502 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
By the time I learned that
professors often
put books on course reserve, it
was too late

51:11.535 --> 51:15.873 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to add it back that semester, or
like when
my professors kept saying, "See
me in office

51:15.906 --> 51:17.808 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
hours," as if we all knew what
that meant.

51:17.841 --> 51:23.047 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But it took a bad grade on a
paper for him
to explain to me what office
hours were, that

51:23.080 --> 51:27.785 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
he was just waiting around in
one place, ready
to answers all my questions.

51:27.818 --> 51:31.855 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What could my college have done
to show me
how much I needed to know
without making me

51:31.889 --> 51:34.425 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
feel dumb or out of my league in
the process?

51:34.458 --> 51:39.029 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This is where well-meaning
administrators
usually start throwing around
the word mentorship.

51:39.063 --> 51:44.234 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But too many colleges still
think of mentoring
as just meetings between two
people, one who

51:44.268 --> 51:48.072 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
knows some stuff and another who
doesn't yet
know that stuff.

51:48.105 --> 51:52.176 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Technically, I had a mentor my
first year
in college, but when I finally
met him, he

51:52.209 --> 51:55.946 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
didn't seem to understand how
confused I was,
in part because he came from a
long line of

51:55.980 --> 51:57.047 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
college-going folks.

51:57.081 --> 52:00.484 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He didn't know how much I didn't
know either.

52:00.517 --> 52:04.855 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Formal mentors like the one my
college assigned
me need to be first-generation
college students

52:04.888 --> 52:09.526 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
themselves or have been trained
by people
intimately familiar with the
challenges students

52:09.560 --> 52:10.728 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
like me faced.

52:10.761 --> 52:13.797 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They need to do more than send
us concerned
e-mails:.

52:13.831 --> 52:16.333 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They need to knock on our
literal doors.

52:16.367 --> 52:20.304 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And they should be compensated
for their work
as mentors, not asked to
volunteer or serve

52:20.337 --> 52:24.241 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
out of some sense of obligation
to help out
a past version of themselves.

52:24.274 --> 52:28.112 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They need to be concretely
valued for the
resource they are, for the
unique survival

52:28.145 --> 52:30.748 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
skills they bring to campus.

52:30.781 --> 52:34.752 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I now work as a novelist and,
believe it or
not, a professor.

52:34.785 --> 52:39.890 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Whenever I'm in front of a group
of new readers
or students, I ask those who
identify as first-generation

52:39.923 --> 52:42.059 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
college people to raise their
hands.

52:42.092 --> 52:43.827 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I then congratulate them.

52:43.861 --> 52:47.531 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I tell them how much it means to
me to meet
them, and I tell them that I'm
one of them.

52:47.564 --> 52:51.602 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, later, after whatever talk
or lecture
I have given, there's almost
always someone

52:51.635 --> 52:54.805 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
who comes up to me and admits
they didn't
raise their hand because they
didn't know

52:54.838 --> 52:59.176 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
being a first-generation college
student was
a fact they could be proud of.

52:59.209 --> 53:04.448 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Only then do I admit to them
something I know
that they don't: When I was in
their place,

53:04.481 --> 53:06.183 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I wouldn't have raised my hand
either.

